WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.239 --> 00:00:06.434
GIRL 1: Who's in there?

2
00:00:06.507 --> 00:00:07.531
GIRL 2: What is it?

3
00:00:07.608 --> 00:00:08.803
GIRL 3: Oh. cool!

4
00:00:10.711 --> 00:00:12.680
GUS: Please don't
touch it. Excuse me.

5
00:00:15.916 --> 00:00:17.851
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

6
00:00:19.987 --> 00:00:21.080
Gus. Gus. Gus!

7
00:00:21.154 --> 00:00:23.487
Where's your project.
Shawn? Did you even do it?

8
00:00:23.557 --> 00:00:25.048
My project? Of course I did.

9
00:00:25.125 --> 00:00:26.650
Uh-huh. when?

10
00:00:26.727 --> 00:00:29.697
When? Last
night. It's right here.

11
00:00:29.763 --> 00:00:31.595
GUS: This head
is to exact scale.

12
00:00:31.665 --> 00:00:36.000
It took me three months to
make it. Yours took five minutes.

13
00:00:36.069 --> 00:00:41.804
No. Gus. you're totally wrong. It
took me a whole hour. Check this out.

14
00:00:45.145 --> 00:00:47.046
(ALL EXCLAIMING EXCITEDLY)

15
00:00:56.890 --> 00:00:58.449
I hate you. Shawn.

16
00:01:13.574 --> 00:01:14.701
Lompoc.

17
00:01:15.609 --> 00:01:17.043
Okay. I did it.

18
00:01:20.147 --> 00:01:21.274
(ALL CHEERING)

19
00:01:22.516 --> 00:01:23.609
Seven in a row!

20
00:01:23.684 --> 00:01:25.880
Eight. The gas station
guy confessed last week.

21
00:01:25.953 --> 00:01:27.430
CARLTON: Oh. I
wouldn't call myself a hero.

22
00:01:27.454 --> 00:01:29.423
I'm just doing my
job. just like all of you.

23
00:01:29.489 --> 00:01:30.729
Hey. that's enough goofing off.

24
00:01:30.757 --> 00:01:33.556
Let's get back to
work. huh? You. too.

25
00:01:33.627 --> 00:01:36.096
Ladies and gentlemen.
Detective Lassiter.

26
00:01:36.163 --> 00:01:37.825
CARLTON: Oh. stop it.

27
00:01:41.935 --> 00:01:43.801
Jules. Shawn.

28
00:01:44.605 --> 00:01:46.403
Is there a problem? With what?

29
00:01:46.473 --> 00:01:49.033
With you? With
me? With the Chief?

30
00:01:49.109 --> 00:01:50.702
She hasn't called in a month.

31
00:01:50.777 --> 00:01:53.110
Is she still mad about me
requisitioning the Segway?

32
00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:55.115
You did that?

33
00:01:55.215 --> 00:01:56.376
No.

34
00:01:56.950 --> 00:01:59.613
Well. I don't really
have time right now.

35
00:01:59.686 --> 00:02:03.885
but the short answer is. we just
haven't really needed any outside help.

36
00:02:03.957 --> 00:02:05.425
Well. what's the long answer?

37
00:02:05.492 --> 00:02:07.358
I mean. throw a "but" in there.

38
00:02:07.427 --> 00:02:08.538
and add something about a dream.

39
00:02:08.562 --> 00:02:10.690
where you and I get thrown
out of a mattress showroom.

40
00:02:10.764 --> 00:02:12.926
Detective Lassiter
is literally on fire.

41
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.410
What kind of fire
are we talking about?

42
00:02:14.434 --> 00:02:16.212
Michael-Jackson-in-the-Pepsi-
commercial fire?

43
00:02:16.236 --> 00:02:18.137
Or misusing-the-
word- "literally" fire?

44
00:02:18.205 --> 00:02:20.731
He's-solved-eight-
cases-in-a-row fire.

45
00:02:20.807 --> 00:02:24.266
Nine. I just remembered
the DeShano case.

46
00:02:24.344 --> 00:02:27.803
Oh. hey. Shawn. What's new?
You still doing the psychic thing?

47
00:02:27.881 --> 00:02:31.045
Is this some sort
of weird dream?

48
00:02:31.118 --> 00:02:35.055
On the last two cases. the first
suspect Lassiter questioned confessed.

49
00:02:35.122 --> 00:02:36.215
It's really magnificent.

50
00:02:36.289 --> 00:02:39.123
We are talking about
Carlton Lassiter. right?

51
00:02:39.192 --> 00:02:40.353
Yea high?

52
00:02:40.427 --> 00:02:42.589
Bats ninth for the
department softball team?

53
00:02:42.663 --> 00:02:44.359
Tenth. We play with a rover.

54
00:02:44.431 --> 00:02:48.664
Spencer. long time. no
see. Or is that "no need"?

55
00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:51.629
I can't believe this.

56
00:02:51.705 --> 00:02:53.674
Oh. believe it. It's real.

57
00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:56.505
They've done a preliminary on the
body down at the marina. Detective.

58
00:02:56.576 --> 00:02:58.135
They're ready for
you at the scene.

59
00:02:58.211 --> 00:03:02.046
Well. I would love to stay
and chat. but duty does call.

60
00:03:03.383 --> 00:03:05.181
Oh. Spencer. you look so sad.

61
00:03:06.319 --> 00:03:08.447
Come on. we'll show
you how real cops do it.

62
00:03:10.824 --> 00:03:11.848
No comeback?

63
00:03:12.759 --> 00:03:15.319
Shawn. that's
slightly embarrassing.

64
00:03:17.164 --> 00:03:19.929
Where did you get that
toot... Suit... The toilet store?

65
00:03:27.874 --> 00:03:29.866
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

66
00:03:31.511 --> 00:03:34.913
Good luck with this one.
Detective. There's no identification.

67
00:03:37.617 --> 00:03:40.781
Nobody's been reported
missing fitting this description.

68
00:03:40.854 --> 00:03:44.450
Oh. Mr. Spencer. Surprised
you didn't take the Segway.

69
00:03:44.958 --> 00:03:46.002
(SOFTLY) She
did know about that.

70
00:03:46.026 --> 00:03:47.494
O'Hara just told me.

71
00:03:47.861 --> 00:03:49.227
Traitor.

72
00:03:49.563 --> 00:03:51.088
I'll deal with you later.

73
00:03:55.535 --> 00:03:57.163
So. what's this new case we got?

74
00:03:57.237 --> 00:03:59.138
A slight error in
grammar there. buddy.

75
00:03:59.206 --> 00:04:01.072
Which part? Got.

76
00:04:01.141 --> 00:04:03.110
I came all the way down
from the office. Shawn.

77
00:04:03.176 --> 00:04:04.872
Gus. don't be a
giant snapping turtle.

78
00:04:05.312 --> 00:04:07.474
We'll have a case
in five minutes.

79
00:04:15.322 --> 00:04:19.282
Nobody can explain these puncture
wounds. We can't rule out an animal attack.

80
00:04:21.862 --> 00:04:25.697
No. No. there's nothing in these
waters with a bite radius that large.

81
00:04:25.766 --> 00:04:31.967
No. this is maybe a boating accident.
the wounds caused by some machinery.

82
00:04:32.506 --> 00:04:34.475
I can't really be
sure at this juncture.

83
00:04:34.541 --> 00:04:37.204
Completely stumped. Hmm.

84
00:04:37.277 --> 00:04:39.246
You're getting
something. Mr. Spencer?

85
00:04:41.014 --> 00:04:42.141
Yes.

86
00:04:44.618 --> 00:04:45.779
Yes. I am.

87
00:04:49.422 --> 00:04:52.017
No. no. no. no. no.
Hold on. okay. I've got it.

88
00:04:52.092 --> 00:04:54.891
The wound on the head was
caused by the edge of a boat.

89
00:04:54.961 --> 00:04:58.523
When he fell in the water.
unconscious. and the...

90
00:04:58.598 --> 00:05:02.763
The wounds on the back. they were
caused by a large industrial crab trap.

91
00:05:05.205 --> 00:05:08.039
Or a whale. Definitely
could have been a whale.

92
00:05:08.108 --> 00:05:12.842
I mean. lost from his pod.
separated. migrating north or south.

93
00:05:12.913 --> 00:05:16.748
and sees our man dead already.
floating up above the surface.

94
00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:18.819
Thinks it's a seal. and then...

95
00:05:19.486 --> 00:05:20.818
Whale.

96
00:05:20.987 --> 00:05:22.319
A whale?

97
00:05:22.389 --> 00:05:23.687
What's your guy got?

98
00:05:23.757 --> 00:05:26.352
Watch and learn.
Jules. Watch and learn.

99
00:05:26.426 --> 00:05:27.450
Or...

100
00:05:27.527 --> 00:05:30.554
Detective. if you don't mind. I'd like
to see what Mr. Spencer has to offer.

101
00:05:33.266 --> 00:05:36.065
All right. look. This is
gonna be a little rough. okay?

102
00:05:36.136 --> 00:05:39.197
I didn't have time for shading.
there's no forced perspective.

103
00:05:39.272 --> 00:05:41.250
If I'd really had my druthers. I
would have done it in charcoal.

104
00:05:41.274 --> 00:05:42.867
You know what I'm talking about.

105
00:05:42.943 --> 00:05:45.188
Look. what I'm trying to say is.
I'm not the artist I'd like to be...

106
00:05:45.212 --> 00:05:46.422
You know what?
Mr. Spencer. enough.

107
00:05:46.446 --> 00:05:49.746
Can you or can you not tell us
who's responsible for this man's death?

108
00:05:49.816 --> 00:05:52.752
If I can present you with a
semi-accurate sketch of the culprit.

109
00:05:52.819 --> 00:05:54.378
is that enough to
get us on this case?

110
00:05:54.454 --> 00:05:55.513
Yes.

111
00:05:56.389 --> 00:05:57.880
All right.

112
00:05:57.958 --> 00:06:00.189
The puncture
wounds. they're the key.

113
00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:03.662
giving me the impression that this
crime could only have been committed

114
00:06:05.465 --> 00:06:06.956
by this guy.

115
00:06:09.936 --> 00:06:10.995
This guy here.

116
00:06:18.311 --> 00:06:19.438
Excuse me.

117
00:06:20.513 --> 00:06:21.742
What?

118
00:06:22.916 --> 00:06:25.681
Chief. where you off to?

119
00:06:27.387 --> 00:06:30.448
So. what. that's a no? Gus?

120
00:06:34.261 --> 00:06:36.253
This is not a boating accident.

121
00:06:40.433 --> 00:06:43.892
<i>I know. you know That
I'm not telling the truth</i>

122
00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:46.963
<i>I know. you know They
just don't have any proof</i>

123
00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:50.340
<i>Embrace the deception
Learn how to bend</i>

124
00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:55.314
<i>Your worst inhibitions tend
to psych you out in the end</i>

125
00:07:03.423 --> 00:07:04.447
You're mad.

126
00:07:04.524 --> 00:07:07.255
No. I'm not mad.
I'm happy. I'm thrilled.

127
00:07:07.327 --> 00:07:08.761
I love looking like an idiot.

128
00:07:08.828 --> 00:07:10.660
Well. that explains your shoes.

129
00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:13.632
You almost closed down our agency
with that little act of yours. Shawn.

130
00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:17.728
Me? You're the one spending all your
extra time at your little side project.

131
00:07:18.371 --> 00:07:21.808
You mean my real job?
Soon to be my only job?

132
00:07:21.875 --> 00:07:23.639
Gus. you're
panicking. Don't panic.

133
00:07:23.710 --> 00:07:26.270
Those bite marks are consistent
with a Tyrannosaurus bite.

134
00:07:26.346 --> 00:07:28.247
You know that? Yes. I know that.

135
00:07:29.382 --> 00:07:30.680
The hard way.

136
00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:34.517
I was canned from the Wyoming Natural
History Museum for that little shot.

137
00:07:34.587 --> 00:07:37.785
The bruises from the teeth didn't
go away for a year. but totally worth it.

138
00:07:37.857 --> 00:07:39.883
It was my best screensaver ever.

139
00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:44.261
Gus. please. connecting a dinosaur
to this case is the least of our worries.

140
00:07:44.331 --> 00:07:46.857
Look. I can stash a toy dinosaur
in the window of the killer.

141
00:07:46.933 --> 00:07:49.368
I can link him to a box of
Dino-bites or Fruity Pebbles.

142
00:07:49.436 --> 00:07:54.306
I can play Six Degrees Of
Dinosaur with you. right now.

143
00:07:57.911 --> 00:08:00.656
You've never been in a movie with
Kevin Bacon or a Dilophosaurus. have you?

144
00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:04.048
How about you play Six
Degrees Of Kiss My Ass?

145
00:08:04.117 --> 00:08:06.916
First of all. that sounds
like a totally disturbing game.

146
00:08:06.987 --> 00:08:10.515
What's weird is that my guess on
the jaw radius was actually spot on.

147
00:08:11.758 --> 00:08:13.989
It almost seems to make sense.

148
00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:16.991
So now you're getting on
board with your own joke theory?

149
00:08:17.063 --> 00:08:19.965
How are you gonna match your
bite radius to the victim. Shawn?

150
00:08:20.033 --> 00:08:22.093
Drag the body to the
Wyoming museum.

151
00:08:22.502 --> 00:08:23.526
Hmm.

152
00:08:25.538 --> 00:08:26.870
I can do you one better.

153
00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:27.964
What?

154
00:08:28.041 --> 00:08:29.907
I need to borrow my Dad's truck.

155
00:08:31.444 --> 00:08:32.810
You coming or what?

156
00:08:34.014 --> 00:08:35.107
That's clearly a no.

157
00:08:36.116 --> 00:08:40.247
The one thing we can be sure of is
the cause of death was not drowning.

158
00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:44.314
Blunt force trauma to the head was
severe enough to knock him unconscious.

159
00:08:44.391 --> 00:08:49.853
More than likely. he fell from some sort of a
platform after knocking himself on the head.

160
00:08:49.929 --> 00:08:51.557
And this is how he
ended up in the water?

161
00:08:51.631 --> 00:08:54.567
No. he landed on something
hard. Dislocated a rib.

162
00:08:54.634 --> 00:08:58.662
He has bruises consistent
with a six. seven or eight-foot fall.

163
00:08:58.872 --> 00:09:03.776
My guess is that he landed on something
else and ultimately expired before

164
00:09:03.843 --> 00:09:05.175
tumbling into the water.

165
00:09:05.245 --> 00:09:08.409
You know. this might be a leap. but
why don't we check the offshore oil rigs?

166
00:09:08.481 --> 00:09:10.677
See if any of them
are missing workers.

167
00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.446
I'll make some calls.

168
00:09:12.519 --> 00:09:14.044
KAREN: Interesting. Detective.

169
00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:17.181
Thanks. Chief. This theory
feels good. It just makes sense.

170
00:09:17.257 --> 00:09:19.692
The work boots. the odd
configuration of the wounds.

171
00:09:19.759 --> 00:09:21.785
You know us. Ted.
it's worth a shot. right?

172
00:09:21.861 --> 00:09:23.205
We don't go out on limbs
too often at the SBPD...

173
00:09:23.229 --> 00:09:25.755
SHAWN: Thank you. I just
need to measure something.

174
00:09:27.667 --> 00:09:31.331
Oh. good. you're all here.
Get ready to be shocked.

175
00:09:31.404 --> 00:09:33.566
Can we get the sheet
off the dead guy. please?

176
00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:35.233
SHAWN: Confirming
the bite radius.

177
00:09:35.308 --> 00:09:36.867
KAREN: No. Mr. Spencer.

178
00:09:36.943 --> 00:09:39.105
Whoa. whoa. Hey. hey.
be careful. This isn't mine.

179
00:09:39.179 --> 00:09:43.879
Mr. Spencer. your antics have always
been a little. let's say. unorthodox.

180
00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:48.285
But let me be as frank as I can be with my
assessment of your most recent behavior.

181
00:09:48.354 --> 00:09:49.754
Seek help.

182
00:09:49.823 --> 00:09:54.227
Chief. sometimes you have to jump
off a cliff. You have to close your eyes.

183
00:09:54.294 --> 00:09:56.422
You have to unhook
your clip. chassis...

184
00:09:57.764 --> 00:09:59.494
(CHANGING
PRONUNCIATION) Chassis?

185
00:10:01.868 --> 00:10:03.200
Climbing thing.

186
00:10:03.269 --> 00:10:05.397
And you have to leap.

187
00:10:05.472 --> 00:10:09.136
Now. I ask you. Chief.
will you leap with me?

188
00:10:09.209 --> 00:10:11.804
Are you thinking
about jumping off a cliff?

189
00:10:12.879 --> 00:10:14.177
Maybe.

190
00:10:24.691 --> 00:10:26.125
Yo.

191
00:10:26.192 --> 00:10:27.455
Dad?

192
00:10:27.527 --> 00:10:29.996
I brought the keys back. Hello?

193
00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:36.132
Okay. This is creepy.
Why is Gus here?

194
00:10:36.202 --> 00:10:38.103
What do you think. Shawn?

195
00:10:38.171 --> 00:10:39.571
He's a hostage?

196
00:10:39.639 --> 00:10:42.302
Perhaps I can shed
some light on that.

197
00:10:42.375 --> 00:10:43.900
Two hostages?

198
00:10:43.977 --> 00:10:46.088
Doug Devette is an old
colleague of mine from the force.

199
00:10:46.112 --> 00:10:48.206
The Chief asked me
to have him drop by.

200
00:10:49.582 --> 00:10:51.016
Why?

201
00:10:51.084 --> 00:10:53.383
Doug is the department
psychologist. Shawn.

202
00:10:53.953 --> 00:10:55.785
What is this. some
sort of intervention?

203
00:10:55.855 --> 00:10:57.016
Yeah. Sort of.

204
00:10:57.090 --> 00:10:59.582
We don't like to use the
term "intervention". Shawn.

205
00:11:00.793 --> 00:11:03.729
Gus? Don't look at me.
I'm here for the cupcakes.

206
00:11:04.697 --> 00:11:06.666
Dad. I am not on drugs.

207
00:11:06.733 --> 00:11:07.877
Oh. nobody thinks that. Shawn.

208
00:11:07.901 --> 00:11:09.145
Well. I'm not completely
sure about that. Doug.

209
00:11:09.169 --> 00:11:10.569
We're all just a
little concerned

210
00:11:10.637 --> 00:11:13.300
that you might be stretching
yourself a bit too thin.

211
00:11:13.373 --> 00:11:16.502
Wasn't my idea. But he's right.
Shawn. You're acting like a nut job.

212
00:11:16.576 --> 00:11:19.136
Just because I take
Gus' giant dinosaur head

213
00:11:19.212 --> 00:11:21.943
down to a dead body
does not make me a nut job.

214
00:11:22.015 --> 00:11:23.381
What?

215
00:11:24.617 --> 00:11:27.086
You took my T-Rex?
My mom gave it to you?

216
00:11:27.153 --> 00:11:28.177
Gladly.

217
00:11:28.254 --> 00:11:31.000
She also gave me some pictures you can
pay me to not show your next girlfriend.

218
00:11:31.024 --> 00:11:32.048
What pictures?

219
00:11:32.125 --> 00:11:34.924
The ones that document your
Terence Trent D'Arby phase.

220
00:11:36.229 --> 00:11:38.721
Whatever. Shawn. You took
Danny Dino to the police station?

221
00:11:38.798 --> 00:11:40.096
No.

222
00:11:40.166 --> 00:11:43.534
Gus. give me some credit.
I took him to the morgue.

223
00:11:43.603 --> 00:11:47.131
Good news. Your
specifications were spot on.

224
00:11:48.808 --> 00:11:52.973
Your father tells me you have
delusions of magical powers.

225
00:11:53.046 --> 00:11:54.070
Delusions?

226
00:11:54.781 --> 00:11:55.874
Really?

227
00:11:56.983 --> 00:11:59.350
Doug. I'm employed as a psychic.

228
00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:01.547
I've solved eighteen
cases this year.

229
00:12:01.621 --> 00:12:05.456
I have business cards and a personalized
coffee mug that backs up the whole thing.

230
00:12:05.525 --> 00:12:08.222
I feel things about people.

231
00:12:12.365 --> 00:12:14.698
You. for instance.
are colorblind.

232
00:12:14.767 --> 00:12:16.759
That's nothing to be ashamed of.

233
00:12:18.938 --> 00:12:22.204
You're also really
stressed about something.

234
00:12:28.881 --> 00:12:30.042
College.

235
00:12:30.883 --> 00:12:32.681
It can be very expensive. Doug.

236
00:12:32.752 --> 00:12:34.084
Oh. wow. that was good. Henry.

237
00:12:34.153 --> 00:12:35.746
Doug. do not be a stooge.

238
00:12:35.822 --> 00:12:39.122
I'm not a stooge. but in
this one case. he was right.

239
00:12:40.193 --> 00:12:41.718
Knock at door.

240
00:12:41.794 --> 00:12:43.228
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

241
00:12:44.097 --> 00:12:46.308
Karen. do you mind? We're in
the middle of an intervention here.

242
00:12:46.332 --> 00:12:48.344
We don't have time for that. But
you're the one who asked for this!

243
00:12:48.368 --> 00:12:50.379
And I thank you. Henry. but
I'm afraid that this can't wait.

244
00:12:50.403 --> 00:12:52.133
We just got a break in the case.

245
00:12:52.205 --> 00:12:53.849
We just found out the
name of the dead man.

246
00:12:53.873 --> 00:12:55.899
You wanna tell him
who he is. Detective?

247
00:12:55.975 --> 00:12:57.034
No.

248
00:12:58.978 --> 00:13:01.106
His name was
Christopher Franzen.

249
00:13:02.382 --> 00:13:04.408
He was a paleontologist.

250
00:13:07.754 --> 00:13:09.086
A dinosaur hunter.

251
00:13:10.623 --> 00:13:11.989
As expected.

252
00:13:12.992 --> 00:13:14.961
Doug. pleasure was all mine.

253
00:13:15.028 --> 00:13:16.519
Oh. no. Shawn. mine.

254
00:13:16.596 --> 00:13:18.030
We should get together.

255
00:13:22.735 --> 00:13:24.079
GUS: All right. here's
what we know so far.

256
00:13:24.103 --> 00:13:26.163
A man. a paleontology professor.

257
00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:28.834
washes ashore with
wounds specific to a dinosaur.

258
00:13:28.908 --> 00:13:30.619
I don't think we can
rule out the possibility

259
00:13:30.643 --> 00:13:33.477
of an island somewhere in the
Pacific where dinosaurs do exist.

260
00:13:33.546 --> 00:13:35.071
And have an appetite
for Jeff Goldblum.

261
00:13:35.148 --> 00:13:36.172
I'm being serious. Shawn.

262
00:13:36.249 --> 00:13:38.309
Well. look who's Mr. Onboard.

263
00:13:38.384 --> 00:13:40.148
And sounding like
a whacked wombat.

264
00:13:40.219 --> 00:13:42.120
Then what is it? I don't know.

265
00:13:42.188 --> 00:13:46.455
It actually scares me that my wild dinosaur
reach landed so close to the bull's-eye.

266
00:13:46.526 --> 00:13:49.086
This guy was possibly killed
by something dinosaur related.

267
00:13:49.162 --> 00:13:52.621
but it was probably a model or
something from the archeology department.

268
00:13:52.699 --> 00:13:54.777
We'll have to spend the
better part of the next 24 hours

269
00:13:54.801 --> 00:13:57.168
sifting through their
entire collection of artifacts.

270
00:13:57.236 --> 00:13:59.262
And by we. I mean. mostly you.

271
00:14:05.545 --> 00:14:07.275
This is all there is?

272
00:14:07.347 --> 00:14:10.215
No. No. no. no. no.
This is just the big stuff.

273
00:14:10.283 --> 00:14:14.311
We got the trilobites in a shoe
box. but the shelf is kind of high.

274
00:14:14.387 --> 00:14:15.855
Whoa. whoa. whoa. whoa.

275
00:14:16.589 --> 00:14:19.368
You've got Pinhead. Chatterbox.
Surgeon and Stitch up there on a shelf?

276
00:14:19.392 --> 00:14:20.826
Shawn. those are Cenobites.

277
00:14:20.893 --> 00:14:22.623
Huh. well what are trilobites?

278
00:14:22.695 --> 00:14:23.924
Fish fossils.

279
00:14:23.996 --> 00:14:25.555
Oh. Gus.

280
00:14:25.665 --> 00:14:28.977
for my sake. at least pretend like you don't
know this stuff off the top of your head.

281
00:14:29.001 --> 00:14:31.232
Do this move.

282
00:14:31.304 --> 00:14:33.000
Tri... Trilo...

283
00:14:33.072 --> 00:14:34.597
What? It'll help
you. I'm serious.

284
00:14:34.674 --> 00:14:36.074
Look. Ethan.

285
00:14:36.142 --> 00:14:38.654
I can honestly say there were
more historically significant items

286
00:14:38.678 --> 00:14:42.171
in the lost and found at the
Taco John's in Porterville.

287
00:14:42.248 --> 00:14:45.514
Yeah. Yeah. it's a little sad.

288
00:14:45.585 --> 00:14:49.488
Word is. the whole
program is going under.

289
00:14:49.555 --> 00:14:50.818
You sure about that?

290
00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:54.190
Look. Professor Franzen would
never really give us a straight answer.

291
00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:57.094
In fact. most nights. he wasn't
around to give us any answers.

292
00:14:57.163 --> 00:14:58.859
He was a pretty crappy advisor.

293
00:14:58.931 --> 00:15:02.231
And when he did show up. he was
late. tired. completely disheveled.

294
00:15:02.301 --> 00:15:03.997
All right? Nobody
really trusted the guy.

295
00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:06.562
Look. do not ever
take a class from him.

296
00:15:06.639 --> 00:15:07.732
He's dead.

297
00:15:07.807 --> 00:15:10.174
Oh. yeah. Then. totally.

298
00:15:16.883 --> 00:15:18.579
Well. this sure was a dead end.

299
00:15:18.651 --> 00:15:23.248
Yep. But at least we were the
first ones to find the dead end.

300
00:15:23.322 --> 00:15:28.488
Oh. come on. He
really is on fire. Literally.

301
00:15:32.732 --> 00:15:35.759
GUS: Look at this. The cops
beat us to the dead guy's house.

302
00:15:35.835 --> 00:15:39.067
I don't know how I feel about the
police department being so proactive.

303
00:15:39.138 --> 00:15:40.299
Feeling the heat?

304
00:15:40.373 --> 00:15:42.017
What. you think I'm afraid
of a little competition?

305
00:15:42.041 --> 00:15:43.771
I know you're
afraid of competition.

306
00:15:43.843 --> 00:15:46.870
Why else would you have purposefully
broken the Battlezone at Pizza Royale?

307
00:15:46.946 --> 00:15:49.916
Dude. you beat me once and only
because you first used the eyepiece

308
00:15:49.982 --> 00:15:51.093
and then revealed
you had pink eye.

309
00:15:51.117 --> 00:15:52.117
Ah.

310
00:15:58.991 --> 00:16:01.017
Let's venture off
the beaten path.

311
00:16:09.068 --> 00:16:10.127
What's wrong?

312
00:16:10.203 --> 00:16:11.980
I'm just trying to figure
out what to do here.

313
00:16:12.004 --> 00:16:14.064
since. as a rule. we
don't break and enter.

314
00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:15.551
What do you mean. we
don't break and enter?

315
00:16:15.575 --> 00:16:17.976
The 2400 Motel.
the Hotel de la Cruz.

316
00:16:18.044 --> 00:16:19.103
the Spellmaster's box.

317
00:16:19.178 --> 00:16:21.943
Yeah. but we really
shouldn't pick this lock.

318
00:16:22.014 --> 00:16:23.676
You know I wanna pick that lock.

319
00:16:23.749 --> 00:16:24.808
Yes. I do.

320
00:16:24.884 --> 00:16:25.977
Watch out.

321
00:16:31.724 --> 00:16:33.625
What are you.
the lock whisperer?

322
00:16:33.693 --> 00:16:35.093
(HIGH-PITCHED GASPING)

323
00:16:35.862 --> 00:16:36.905
Channeling Michael Jackson?

324
00:16:36.929 --> 00:16:38.522
(CLICKS) Shh!

325
00:16:38.598 --> 00:16:39.896
Who heard the second click?

326
00:16:39.966 --> 00:16:41.525
I heard the second click.

327
00:16:45.605 --> 00:16:46.664
Really?

328
00:16:51.244 --> 00:16:52.678
Come on!

329
00:16:58.718 --> 00:16:59.777
I can't see anything.

330
00:16:59.852 --> 00:17:01.480
Oh. I got it. I got it.

331
00:17:04.257 --> 00:17:05.257
(GROANS)

332
00:17:05.358 --> 00:17:07.054
Gus. that thing is
brighter than the sun.

333
00:17:07.126 --> 00:17:08.437
I think you just
gave me glaucoma.

334
00:17:08.461 --> 00:17:10.191
You can't give someone glaucoma.

335
00:17:13.032 --> 00:17:14.125
Thank you.

336
00:17:15.835 --> 00:17:19.135
Wow. this is better than the
entire university department.

337
00:17:19.205 --> 00:17:20.229
Sure is.

338
00:17:20.306 --> 00:17:25.040
And his digging equipment is some heavy-duty
stuff. Looks like some shovels are missing.

339
00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:29.315
GUS: Part of a
portable light kit.

340
00:17:30.683 --> 00:17:32.083
A lot of brushes.

341
00:17:35.254 --> 00:17:40.158
And fine finishing equipment. which I
would assume he was only using in the lab.

342
00:17:42.828 --> 00:17:44.456
Dude. I got something. What?

343
00:17:45.197 --> 00:17:47.709
He was the worst tic-tac-toe
player in the history of the world.

344
00:17:47.733 --> 00:17:50.328
I'm investigating. and
you're analyzing his doodles?

345
00:17:50.403 --> 00:17:53.396
Doodles are the
window to the soul. Gus.

346
00:17:53.472 --> 00:17:57.568
Maybe that's the epiglottis.
Where's the uvula?

347
00:17:57.643 --> 00:17:59.373
Lassiter's here.

348
00:17:59.445 --> 00:18:02.643
That guy's. like. five minutes
behind us. everywhere we go.

349
00:18:02.715 --> 00:18:04.513
Don't sleep in the nude tonight.

350
00:18:16.429 --> 00:18:19.263
Spencer. enjoying your
time riding my behind?

351
00:18:19.332 --> 00:18:20.891
Definitely not in the nude.

352
00:18:20.967 --> 00:18:23.493
This lock is too high-tech
for a backyard shed.

353
00:18:23.569 --> 00:18:24.813
We got to find somebody
who can crack the code.

354
00:18:24.837 --> 00:18:27.500
There's already someone
here who can do that.

355
00:18:27.573 --> 00:18:28.836
That person

356
00:18:29.308 --> 00:18:30.332
is me.

357
00:18:30.409 --> 00:18:32.139
Well. make yourself useful.

358
00:18:35.114 --> 00:18:38.050
I need you to step back. please.
Give me some room to operate.

359
00:18:41.454 --> 00:18:42.717
Further. please.

360
00:18:44.857 --> 00:18:46.335
Further. Jules. could
you help me out here?

361
00:18:46.359 --> 00:18:50.160
Just get him back onto the
cobblestone. That's good. That's good.

362
00:18:51.964 --> 00:18:53.330
Thank you.

363
00:18:53.399 --> 00:18:54.399
(CLEARS THROAT)

364
00:18:54.467 --> 00:18:55.594
(SIGHS)

365
00:18:55.668 --> 00:18:57.637
I am sensing
the first two digits.

366
00:19:00.673 --> 00:19:02.005
(SOFTLY) What is it. 31?

367
00:19:02.074 --> 00:19:03.940
Gus. help me out
here. Come on. buddy.

368
00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:05.010
Pfft!

369
00:19:05.077 --> 00:19:06.602
You can have my
Tony Gwynn rookie.

370
00:19:06.679 --> 00:19:07.703
Twenty-five.

371
00:19:07.780 --> 00:19:09.578
Twenty

372
00:19:09.649 --> 00:19:11.083
five.

373
00:19:13.319 --> 00:19:15.015
Eight? Three.

374
00:19:16.188 --> 00:19:17.588
Three.

375
00:19:18.557 --> 00:19:19.957
Four? Two.

376
00:19:20.026 --> 00:19:22.518
And two.

377
00:19:23.129 --> 00:19:26.998
There's one more.
Wait. There's one more.

378
00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:29.159
Nine.

379
00:19:41.681 --> 00:19:42.979
That's amazing.

380
00:19:43.816 --> 00:19:45.284
I'll give you that one.

381
00:19:48.921 --> 00:19:50.913
I can't see a thing in
here. GUS: Oh. I got it.

382
00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:52.788
Wait. I'm sensing
a light switch.

383
00:19:55.795 --> 00:19:57.627
Tools are missing.

384
00:19:57.697 --> 00:19:59.063
Good work. Detective.

385
00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:04.603
He had a blunt force trauma. That could
be supplied by one of these missing items.

386
00:20:04.670 --> 00:20:07.663
Maybe this rock hammer.
or this medium shovel.

387
00:20:08.407 --> 00:20:09.932
But where would they be?

388
00:20:10.009 --> 00:20:13.776
In the bed of his pickup. It wasn't
parked out front or at the university.

389
00:20:13.846 --> 00:20:16.315
We find that truck. we
find the murder weapon.

390
00:20:16.382 --> 00:20:18.146
Let's go. O'Hara.
burning daylight.

391
00:20:19.118 --> 00:20:20.279
Excuse us.

392
00:20:23.322 --> 00:20:24.449
Man. you missed the truck?

393
00:20:24.523 --> 00:20:25.752
I'm not the psychic.

394
00:20:31.964 --> 00:20:33.057
What?

395
00:20:33.666 --> 00:20:38.570
Why would someone frequent a
fruit stand that's over 50 miles away?

396
00:20:39.872 --> 00:20:41.306
They like pomegranate?

397
00:20:53.085 --> 00:20:55.953
Yeah. I know him. He
was my best customer.

398
00:20:56.021 --> 00:21:00.083
Don't know his name. But he
comes by every night before closing.

399
00:21:00.159 --> 00:21:02.025
Did you ever see
which way he went?

400
00:21:02.094 --> 00:21:03.494
Yeah.

401
00:21:03.562 --> 00:21:06.532
Always up the hill.
That's all I'd see.

402
00:21:06.599 --> 00:21:08.761
Although. every once in a while

403
00:21:08.834 --> 00:21:11.804
I see him come back down
the hill. early in the morning.

404
00:21:12.171 --> 00:21:13.571
Hmm. Well.

405
00:21:13.639 --> 00:21:15.117
thank you very much.
Gus. you got anything else?

406
00:21:15.141 --> 00:21:16.769
Yes. Is that peach
pie in the back?

407
00:21:16.842 --> 00:21:17.901
Yeah.

408
00:21:38.531 --> 00:21:40.659
Another dead-end.
Let's turn around.

409
00:21:42.434 --> 00:21:45.165
No! Hold on a second.

410
00:21:55.781 --> 00:21:59.183
This looks like a place
someone's been sneaking into.

411
00:22:09.295 --> 00:22:10.524
SHAWN: What is this?

412
00:22:10.596 --> 00:22:13.964
Looks like some kind of
farm land or grazing plain.

413
00:22:14.033 --> 00:22:18.494
Oh. look at that. This is like that
movie. the one with Sigourney Weaver.

414
00:22:18.571 --> 00:22:19.834
<i>Aliens?</i> No.

415
00:22:19.905 --> 00:22:21.339
<i>Alien?</i>

416
00:22:21.407 --> 00:22:22.898
No. <i>Alien: Resurrection.</i>

417
00:22:22.975 --> 00:22:25.103
Gus. the one with the
holes and Shia LaBeouf.

418
00:22:25.177 --> 00:22:27.146
They had holes in Shia LaBeouf?

419
00:22:27.213 --> 00:22:29.614
The holes are in the
ground. dude. Like that.

420
00:22:29.682 --> 00:22:32.049
And Jon Voight was
walking around all crazy.

421
00:22:32.117 --> 00:22:33.779
Oh. <i>Anaconda.</i>

422
00:22:33.853 --> 00:22:35.287
Man. never mind.

423
00:22:35.354 --> 00:22:37.516
<i>Gorillas in the Mist?
Death and the Maiden?</i>

424
00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:38.614
No.

425
00:22:38.691 --> 00:22:39.750
<i>Half Moon Street?</i>

426
00:22:39.825 --> 00:22:41.191
Just let it go.

427
00:22:45.965 --> 00:22:47.160
I'll be damned.

428
00:22:47.233 --> 00:22:48.257
(GUN FIRES)

429
00:22:48.334 --> 00:22:49.996
What? Somebody's shooting at us!

430
00:22:50.069 --> 00:22:51.069
(GUN FIRES)

431
00:22:51.136 --> 00:22:52.968
(GUS SCREAMING)

432
00:22:53.038 --> 00:22:54.583
Oh. God. They're shooting
at us! GUS: We're gonna die!

433
00:22:54.607 --> 00:22:58.703
SHAWN: For sure! Run.
Gus! Gus. run like the wind!

434
00:22:58.777 --> 00:22:59.777
Get up!

435
00:23:02.114 --> 00:23:03.114
(BOTH GASPING)

436
00:23:03.182 --> 00:23:05.742
GUS: Okay. Hold the door.

437
00:23:05.818 --> 00:23:09.482
Come on. get in the
car! Hurry up. Shawn!

438
00:23:09.555 --> 00:23:12.821
Start it! Start it! Go! Go!

439
00:23:12.892 --> 00:23:15.054
Dude! Look at the road
when you're driving!

440
00:23:15.127 --> 00:23:16.652
I'm staying down for safety.

441
00:23:16.729 --> 00:23:18.459
He was shooting
directly into the air. Gus.

442
00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:20.089
Bullets go up. they
have to come down.

443
00:23:20.165 --> 00:23:22.544
Do you know what the trajectory
would have to be for that to happen?

444
00:23:22.568 --> 00:23:24.127
Don't you dare argue
physics with me.

445
00:23:24.203 --> 00:23:26.297
Not while in the process
of almost being killed.

446
00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:37.406
Didn't you see the
"Trespassers Will Be Shot" sign?

447
00:23:39.084 --> 00:23:41.246
Oh. yeah. it totally said that.

448
00:23:41.921 --> 00:23:42.921
My bad.

449
00:23:47.960 --> 00:23:50.327
Mr. Spencer. if you have
any substantial information

450
00:23:50.396 --> 00:23:53.560
concerning the Christopher
Franzen case. please get on with it.

451
00:23:53.632 --> 00:23:54.656
(CLUCKS)

452
00:23:54.733 --> 00:23:56.702
I've got something.

453
00:23:56.769 --> 00:23:57.828
It's a cluck.

454
00:23:57.903 --> 00:23:58.996
A cluck?

455
00:23:59.505 --> 00:24:02.270
(CLUCKING)

456
00:24:03.776 --> 00:24:05.802
Actually. there's
two. Two clucks?

457
00:24:05.878 --> 00:24:07.608
A cluck. cluck here.

458
00:24:12.284 --> 00:24:15.345
A cluck. cluck there.

459
00:24:15.421 --> 00:24:17.049
Here a cluck. there a...

460
00:24:17.122 --> 00:24:18.146
Cluck?

461
00:24:18.223 --> 00:24:19.486
Everywhere a...

462
00:24:19.558 --> 00:24:21.186
(CLUCKING)

463
00:24:21.260 --> 00:24:24.788
Let me guess. You have a
name. Macdonald. perhaps?

464
00:24:24.863 --> 00:24:28.322
No. No. it's a farm. With
a farmer. An old farmer.

465
00:24:28.400 --> 00:24:31.199
Farmer "Shootypants."

466
00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:33.081
That's a nickname. I don't
think that's his actual handle.

467
00:24:33.105 --> 00:24:34.129
CARLTON: I got it!

468
00:24:34.206 --> 00:24:35.970
Lassiter found the
paleontologist's truck.

469
00:24:36.041 --> 00:24:37.134
You helped.

470
00:24:37.209 --> 00:24:38.472
I did help. It was his hunch.

471
00:24:38.544 --> 00:24:40.809
It was down at the Old
Marina. I just had a feeling.

472
00:24:40.879 --> 00:24:43.815
I also found the prints of a certain
grad student named Ethan Robinson.

473
00:24:43.882 --> 00:24:46.249
along with a stack of
letters from said grad student

474
00:24:46.318 --> 00:24:48.549
demanding the professor
stop ruining his life.

475
00:24:48.620 --> 00:24:50.646
We're sending a car
over to pick him up.

476
00:24:51.690 --> 00:24:54.091
Oh. I'm sorry. Am I
interrupting your trance?

477
00:24:54.526 --> 00:24:55.550
I don't buy it.

478
00:24:55.627 --> 00:24:59.723
Which part? The damning
evidence or the murder weapon?

479
00:24:59.798 --> 00:25:03.098
There's more going on in this
guy's life. Chief. I'm sensing...

480
00:25:07.272 --> 00:25:08.296
Digging.

481
00:25:08.374 --> 00:25:10.051
Yeah. the archeology
department was going under.

482
00:25:10.075 --> 00:25:13.568
He was trying to make a big discovery.
put them on the map. get more funding.

483
00:25:13.645 --> 00:25:18.515
The farm. I can see the
name of the farm. It's Wa...

484
00:25:18.584 --> 00:25:21.144
Wal...

485
00:25:21.220 --> 00:25:25.988
Walker Farms. Yeah. we got that
lead off the phone records. Yesterday.

486
00:25:26.058 --> 00:25:28.503
Apparently. our victim made a
series of phone calls to the farmer.

487
00:25:28.527 --> 00:25:31.190
trying to buy some of his
land. but it wasn't for sale.

488
00:25:31.263 --> 00:25:33.198
The farmer was
forthcoming. cooperative...

489
00:25:33.265 --> 00:25:34.756
Definitely not a suspect.

490
00:25:34.833 --> 00:25:36.131
Anything else?

491
00:25:36.201 --> 00:25:39.137
I have to say. you have
been very thorough.

492
00:25:39.204 --> 00:25:41.400
We're just doing what
any good cops would do.

493
00:25:43.008 --> 00:25:44.008
(GASPS)

494
00:25:50.282 --> 00:25:51.375
Shawn. what are you doing?

495
00:25:51.450 --> 00:25:53.510
Yeah. what are we doing. Shawn?

496
00:25:53.585 --> 00:25:55.520
I need to borrow some
tools. What kind of tools?

497
00:25:55.587 --> 00:25:58.523
Digging tools. A little excavation
project we've got going on.

498
00:25:58.590 --> 00:25:59.868
Are you still on
that dinosaur thing?

499
00:25:59.892 --> 00:26:01.169
We're still on that
dinosaur thing?

500
00:26:01.193 --> 00:26:02.404
What. is there an echo in here?

501
00:26:02.428 --> 00:26:04.226
Yes. we're still on
the dinosaur thing.

502
00:26:04.296 --> 00:26:07.289
We stepped foot on the far end
of this guy Walker's farm in Ojai.

503
00:26:07.366 --> 00:26:09.301
and he starts blasting
us with buckshot.

504
00:26:09.368 --> 00:26:11.713
We know our dead guy was there
every night leading up to his death.

505
00:26:11.737 --> 00:26:13.933
digging around the
periphery of this property.

506
00:26:14.006 --> 00:26:17.443
No. Shawn. Wait. I don't
want you borrowing my tools.

507
00:26:17.509 --> 00:26:19.229
Gus will leave his
class ring as collateral.

508
00:26:19.278 --> 00:26:20.922
No. I won't. No. I won't.
Yes. you will. Sure. you will.

509
00:26:20.946 --> 00:26:23.006
No. I won't. I
can't support this.

510
00:26:23.082 --> 00:26:26.018
Well. there's a shocker.
you not being supportive.

511
00:26:26.085 --> 00:26:27.195
Would you shut up and listen?

512
00:26:27.219 --> 00:26:31.281
I'm saying I can't support you going
somewhere where you could get shot.

513
00:26:31.356 --> 00:26:33.348
What are you... Are
you worried about me?

514
00:26:33.425 --> 00:26:35.503
Shawn. I've been worried about
you since you were three years old

515
00:26:35.527 --> 00:26:37.689
and started eating
your own toenails.

516
00:26:38.397 --> 00:26:42.266
Well. Dad. I'll be fine. Okay? We're
not gonna go anywhere near the house.

517
00:26:42.334 --> 00:26:45.447
And if it'll make you feel any better. I
will stand behind Gus the entire time.

518
00:26:45.471 --> 00:26:46.815
No. you won't. No.
you won't. Yes. I will.

519
00:26:46.839 --> 00:26:47.882
Oh. yes. I will. You wanna bet?

520
00:26:47.906 --> 00:26:51.206
I don't like it. It
doesn't feel right.

521
00:26:51.276 --> 00:26:52.642
I know feelings.

522
00:26:52.711 --> 00:26:53.872
Pardon me?

523
00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.349
Did you just say.
"I know feelings"?

524
00:27:02.921 --> 00:27:05.220
GUS: Perfect. This will be easy.

525
00:27:05.290 --> 00:27:08.920
No. there's a pattern here.
Those guys dig with a reason.

526
00:27:08.994 --> 00:27:10.223
How do you know that?

527
00:27:10.295 --> 00:27:14.027
Because I worked at the museum for almost
an entire weekend before I got canned.

528
00:27:16.034 --> 00:27:18.834
<i>SHAWN: He was the worst tic-tac-toe
player in the history of the world.</i>

529
00:27:19.338 --> 00:27:20.772
(SOFTLY) Wait a second.

530
00:27:21.406 --> 00:27:24.570
Those weren't tic-tac-toe boards.
Those were all the places he dug.

531
00:27:24.643 --> 00:27:26.077
There were. like.
twenty-five X's.

532
00:27:26.145 --> 00:27:27.670
No way he scored that often.

533
00:27:27.746 --> 00:27:32.047
The X's were misses. In
this case. O marks the spot.

534
00:27:43.061 --> 00:27:44.495
And that's the O.

535
00:27:53.372 --> 00:27:55.841
This is the only hole
filled by a bulldozer.

536
00:27:55.908 --> 00:27:58.969
No self-respecting paleontologist
would use a bulldozer.

537
00:28:00.612 --> 00:28:01.705
Why do you know that?

538
00:28:01.780 --> 00:28:03.009
Because. Shawn. if you use...

539
00:28:03.081 --> 00:28:04.572
Gus. I don't actually
wanna know.

540
00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:05.845
Then don't ask.

541
00:28:06.018 --> 00:28:07.042
Here.

542
00:28:07.119 --> 00:28:09.179
This shouldn't take
long. Grab a shovel.

543
00:28:10.789 --> 00:28:12.724
And keep an eye
out for that farmer.

544
00:28:20.832 --> 00:28:22.164
How you doing on your side?

545
00:28:22.234 --> 00:28:23.862
Good! Solid!

546
00:28:24.937 --> 00:28:26.769
Holding up.

547
00:28:26.838 --> 00:28:28.238
Shawn! What?

548
00:28:28.307 --> 00:28:31.072
I'm keeping watch. That's
how the other guy died.

549
00:28:32.444 --> 00:28:34.003
What? You're not concerned?

550
00:28:37.182 --> 00:28:38.775
All right. I get it!

551
00:28:39.851 --> 00:28:41.285
It's my turn.

552
00:28:42.154 --> 00:28:43.782
(SHAWN GRUNTING)

553
00:28:46.892 --> 00:28:49.123
This is the end of the
loose dirt. Be careful.

554
00:28:55.267 --> 00:28:56.963
This is weird.

555
00:28:57.035 --> 00:28:59.004
What? That there's
rocks in the ground?

556
00:28:59.071 --> 00:29:00.334
These aren't rocks.

557
00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:06.034
These are fossils. But they've
been processed. finished off. Residue.

558
00:29:06.111 --> 00:29:09.240
Rocks chipped away. Stuff
you would normally do in a lab.

559
00:29:10.349 --> 00:29:11.908
Franzen found something.

560
00:29:14.119 --> 00:29:16.054
Why wouldn't he just take it out

561
00:29:16.121 --> 00:29:18.647
and do the work in the lab
where it should be done?

562
00:29:21.126 --> 00:29:22.219
Unless...

563
00:29:23.095 --> 00:29:25.223
Unless it was too big to move.

564
00:29:25.297 --> 00:29:28.597
Dude. I'm gonna
get the leaf blower.

565
00:29:28.667 --> 00:29:30.397
You brought a leaf blower?

566
00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:43.614
(COUGHING)

567
00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:46.884
You got to be kidding me.

568
00:29:48.253 --> 00:29:49.949
I just discovered a dinosaur.

569
00:29:57.095 --> 00:29:59.826
Filling that hole was
the worst idea ever.

570
00:29:59.898 --> 00:30:02.129
Huh. It had to be done. Gus.

571
00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:05.534
We have to save it for when
we unmask Franzen's killer.

572
00:30:05.604 --> 00:30:07.368
I still don't get it.

573
00:30:07.439 --> 00:30:09.135
He was on the trail of a...

574
00:30:09.207 --> 00:30:12.644
Of a fossil graveyard. It led
him right to Deacon Farms.

575
00:30:12.711 --> 00:30:15.180
the farmer wouldn't
let him dig on the land.

576
00:30:15.247 --> 00:30:17.842
so he takes matters into
his own hands after hours.

577
00:30:18.517 --> 00:30:20.816
Why wouldn't the
farmer let him dig?

578
00:30:20.886 --> 00:30:23.287
Maybe he didn't want
his farm disturbed.

579
00:30:24.923 --> 00:30:27.483
A dig like that is worth
millions to a landowner.

580
00:30:27.559 --> 00:30:30.222
And the fossils I discovered
weren't even on crop land.

581
00:30:30.295 --> 00:30:31.388
You discovered?

582
00:30:31.463 --> 00:30:33.591
Don't try to take away my
dinosaur discovery. Shawn.

583
00:30:33.665 --> 00:30:37.124
I wouldn't dream of it. I'm sorry. it
was all you. I'm pretty proud of you.

584
00:30:37.736 --> 00:30:39.864
Don't you think once
they unearth that thing.

585
00:30:39.938 --> 00:30:42.908
there would be a swarm of people
crashing in from all over the world?

586
00:30:42.974 --> 00:30:44.738
Why didn't he just
lease the land?

587
00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:46.073
I don't get it.

588
00:30:47.446 --> 00:30:48.778
I've got an idea.

589
00:30:48.847 --> 00:30:50.008
What?

590
00:30:50.082 --> 00:30:51.243
Let's ask him.

591
00:30:51.316 --> 00:30:52.340
What?

592
00:30:52.417 --> 00:30:54.617
We're pretty sure we just
found a cold-blooded murderer.

593
00:30:54.686 --> 00:30:56.631
and you wanna go to his
house and ask him about it?

594
00:30:56.655 --> 00:30:58.214
We can ask nicely. No.

595
00:30:58.290 --> 00:31:01.351
All right. all right. We
come up with a cover story.

596
00:31:01.426 --> 00:31:03.657
We're vacuum salesmen. No.

597
00:31:03.729 --> 00:31:06.893
Traveling gypsies. No. no. no.

598
00:31:06.965 --> 00:31:10.231
We'll do <i>Of Mice and
Men.</i> I'm Lennie. No.

599
00:31:10.302 --> 00:31:11.361
(CHILD-LIKE VOICE) George.

600
00:31:11.436 --> 00:31:13.514
you said that I could take
care of those rabbits. George.

601
00:31:13.538 --> 00:31:14.538
Shawn...

602
00:31:14.606 --> 00:31:16.472
And later on you're
going to cook those beans.

603
00:31:16.541 --> 00:31:17.565
Shawn!

604
00:31:17.642 --> 00:31:18.701
Beans make me go...

605
00:31:19.211 --> 00:31:20.873
No Lennie.

606
00:31:20.946 --> 00:31:23.291
Gus. you know how long I've
been waiting to pull out my Lennie?

607
00:31:23.315 --> 00:31:26.843
No. Shawn. We do the National
Paleontology Society thing. as agreed.

608
00:31:26.918 --> 00:31:28.853
And we keep it
very. very simple.

609
00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:31.549
It's not as much fun as
whipping out my Lennie.

610
00:31:31.623 --> 00:31:32.783
And why are we stopping here?

611
00:31:32.824 --> 00:31:34.588
Have you tried these peaches?

612
00:31:36.828 --> 00:31:38.660
You're back? Yes. sir we are.

613
00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:40.221
We're addicted to your citrus.

614
00:31:40.298 --> 00:31:42.258
Peaches aren't citrus.
Shawn. They're stone fruit.

615
00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:44.030
It's the same thing.
No. not the same thing.

616
00:31:44.102 --> 00:31:46.571
They have pits. peaches.
cherries. plums and apricots.

617
00:31:46.638 --> 00:31:50.370
I can't do this with you right now.
Does your fruit come from Walker Farms?

618
00:31:50.442 --> 00:31:53.469
Oh. no. We grow on our
own little parcel of land.

619
00:31:53.545 --> 00:31:57.175
Deacon Walker Farms used to
be a supplier of ours years ago.

620
00:31:57.249 --> 00:31:59.912
but they don't grow nearly
as much as they used to.

621
00:32:01.787 --> 00:32:03.551
Thank you so much
for your information.

622
00:32:03.622 --> 00:32:07.059
If you have a moment. my friend and I would
like to buy every peach on that truck.

623
00:32:07.125 --> 00:32:08.405
Including the one you're eating.

624
00:32:16.768 --> 00:32:18.446
You're sure you don't want
to do <i>Of Mice and Men?</i>

625
00:32:18.470 --> 00:32:19.836
You so much as slur one word.

626
00:32:19.905 --> 00:32:22.568
I'll give you an Indian burn so
hot. your socks will catch fire.

627
00:32:22.641 --> 00:32:25.805
Indian burn? Haven't been
threatened with that this millennium.

628
00:32:25.877 --> 00:32:28.142
Take your shot if
your ulna feels safe.

629
00:32:28.213 --> 00:32:30.478
I don't think the
ulna is in the forearm.

630
00:32:30.549 --> 00:32:32.279
Trust me. it is.

631
00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:33.613
How can you Indian burn a bone?

632
00:32:33.685 --> 00:32:35.051
Stop analyzing my threat.

633
00:32:35.120 --> 00:32:36.679
Get it right. I got it right.

634
00:32:37.556 --> 00:32:38.649
Deacon Walker?

635
00:32:38.723 --> 00:32:40.055
Sullivan Walker.

636
00:32:40.125 --> 00:32:41.684
Is Deacon Walker home?

637
00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:43.786
There is no Deacon Walker.

638
00:32:43.862 --> 00:32:44.921
That's confusing.

639
00:32:47.165 --> 00:32:48.929
I got nothing. Gus?

640
00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.435
Then why name the farm
Deacon Walker Farms?

641
00:32:51.503 --> 00:32:52.814
It used to be called
Deacon Walker.

642
00:32:52.838 --> 00:32:55.364
Roger Deacon was my
partner. He's not anymore.

643
00:32:55.440 --> 00:32:58.604
Oh. That cleans it up
nicely. May we come in?

644
00:32:58.677 --> 00:33:00.373
No. What do you want?

645
00:33:00.445 --> 00:33:02.676
We're from the National
Paleontological Society...

646
00:33:02.747 --> 00:33:03.840
Not interested.

647
00:33:06.418 --> 00:33:08.319
Clearly. he's not interested.

648
00:33:12.991 --> 00:33:17.019
We would like to make you a very sizable
offer on a very small portion of your...

649
00:33:25.403 --> 00:33:28.202
(CHILD-LIKE VOICE) Hello.
my name is Lennie. I like to...

650
00:33:33.011 --> 00:33:35.207
You think he'd open
up if we knocked again?

651
00:33:40.452 --> 00:33:42.296
I'm glad it only took us
an hour to get up here.

652
00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:44.221
Not like I wasted a whole day.

653
00:33:46.691 --> 00:33:48.557
Franzen dug up here. too?

654
00:33:59.938 --> 00:34:01.338
No. he didn't.

655
00:34:01.406 --> 00:34:04.604
These are all new and dug with a
bulldozer. A real paleontologist...

656
00:34:04.676 --> 00:34:07.305
Would never use such
an indelicate tool. I got it.

657
00:34:08.547 --> 00:34:10.175
So. our farmer's
been digging. too?

658
00:34:10.248 --> 00:34:15.414
Right. but if the goldmine's out
there. why is he digging over here?

659
00:34:18.023 --> 00:34:19.218
(PHONE RINGING)

660
00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:24.586
It's my Dad. Think he
wants his leaf blower back?

661
00:34:27.198 --> 00:34:29.724
Shawn? Shawn. you're not anywhere
near that farmhouse. are you?

662
00:34:29.801 --> 00:34:31.497
Dad. how dare
you? Of course not.

663
00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:34.267
Good. Stay away. Shawn. I
know where I remember that farm.

664
00:34:34.339 --> 00:34:37.241
Deacon Walker Farm. I was
up there about 20 years ago.

665
00:34:37.309 --> 00:34:40.507
A girl reported that her boyfriend
went missing. Roger Deacon.

666
00:34:40.579 --> 00:34:44.016
He was a partner in the farm.
He was never found. Shawn.

667
00:34:44.082 --> 00:34:45.641
Never found?

668
00:34:45.717 --> 00:34:48.329
That's right. the farmer claimed he
went back to England or some nonsense.

669
00:34:48.353 --> 00:34:50.219
The point is. we never
found out where he went.

670
00:34:50.288 --> 00:34:52.587
I think I might
know where he is.

671
00:34:52.657 --> 00:34:53.920
<i>Where?</i>

672
00:34:53.992 --> 00:34:55.032
I might be looking at him.

673
00:34:55.093 --> 00:34:56.425
Shawn? Got to go.

674
00:34:57.262 --> 00:34:58.696
Shawn! God...

675
00:35:00.131 --> 00:35:01.565
Dude. What?

676
00:35:05.203 --> 00:35:07.570
It now appears a lot of our
evidence is circumstantial.

677
00:35:07.639 --> 00:35:09.870
I mean. we're checking
the grad student's alibi.

678
00:35:09.941 --> 00:35:11.519
but I'm not as confident
as I'd like to be.

679
00:35:11.543 --> 00:35:12.875
Shawn Spencer's on line one.

680
00:35:12.944 --> 00:35:14.003
What does he want?

681
00:35:14.079 --> 00:35:16.674
He wants us to go meet him
in the Ojai Valley somewhere.

682
00:35:16.748 --> 00:35:18.444
We're in the middle
of the Franzen case.

683
00:35:18.516 --> 00:35:19.677
I told him that.

684
00:35:19.751 --> 00:35:23.119
He guarantees that in ten minutes.
he can solve the case. nab the killer.

685
00:35:23.188 --> 00:35:25.623
close an additional
unsolved murder and...

686
00:35:27.859 --> 00:35:29.122
And what?

687
00:35:30.061 --> 00:35:31.962
Unearth a dinosaur.

688
00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:34.329
Well. I'm curious.

689
00:35:44.109 --> 00:35:47.136
This is as far as
my property goes.

690
00:35:47.212 --> 00:35:49.272
That's all there is.

691
00:35:49.347 --> 00:35:54.285
Well. I've answered all your questions.
Detective. What more do you want from me?

692
00:35:54.352 --> 00:35:55.786
I'm not entirely sure. sir.

693
00:35:55.854 --> 00:35:58.756
We just have one more
person we need you to talk to.

694
00:36:01.393 --> 00:36:03.055
Lennie?

695
00:36:03.128 --> 00:36:04.187
Lennie?

696
00:36:04.262 --> 00:36:05.560
Don't even ask.

697
00:36:06.665 --> 00:36:08.463
My name is not
Lennie. Mr. Walker.

698
00:36:08.533 --> 00:36:10.764
But if it were. I would
have been amazing.

699
00:36:10.835 --> 00:36:12.913
No. you wouldn't have. It
would've brought tears. Gus.

700
00:36:12.937 --> 00:36:14.235
Guys. the point?

701
00:36:14.305 --> 00:36:17.798
The truth is I'm a psychic.

702
00:36:17.876 --> 00:36:19.845
I work for the SBPD.

703
00:36:19.911 --> 00:36:23.871
And the mystic vibrations of the sea
have brought me here to solve not one.

704
00:36:23.948 --> 00:36:26.474
but two murders.

705
00:36:27.285 --> 00:36:28.309
You're a what?

706
00:36:28.386 --> 00:36:31.550
Christopher Franzen was a
persistent annoyance. huh?

707
00:36:31.623 --> 00:36:34.183
He couldn't help it. His
department was going under.

708
00:36:34.259 --> 00:36:37.957
<i>He was desperate to find something
significant to save his career.</i>

709
00:36:38.029 --> 00:36:41.090
<i>And he knew that your
property held the key.</i>

710
00:36:41.166 --> 00:36:43.431
But you wouldn't let him dig.

711
00:36:43.501 --> 00:36:45.868
You couldn't let him dig.

712
00:36:45.937 --> 00:36:48.372
So he did what any
self-respecting paleontologist

713
00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:51.274
on the verge of a nervous
breakdown would do.

714
00:36:51.342 --> 00:36:56.645
<i>He dug anyway. secretly.
under the blanket of night.</i>

715
00:36:56.715 --> 00:36:58.547
<i>and into the early morning.</i>

716
00:36:58.616 --> 00:37:03.111
<i>And he dug. and he dug.
And he found something.</i>

717
00:37:10.361 --> 00:37:12.330
And that's when you found him.

718
00:37:12.397 --> 00:37:14.798
You knew the
magnitude of the find.

719
00:37:14.866 --> 00:37:16.698
Once word got out. you'd
never be able to keep

720
00:37:16.768 --> 00:37:18.737
the rest of the world
from digging here. too.

721
00:37:18.803 --> 00:37:21.967
And you couldn't have the rest of the
world digging here either. could you?

722
00:37:22.040 --> 00:37:24.236
Shawn!

723
00:37:24.309 --> 00:37:25.800
Dad? What are you doing here?

724
00:37:25.877 --> 00:37:27.743
I was worried.

725
00:37:27.812 --> 00:37:29.144
About my tools.

726
00:37:29.214 --> 00:37:30.238
(SIGHS)

727
00:37:30.315 --> 00:37:31.339
What?

728
00:37:31.416 --> 00:37:33.627
If I'd known that you're finally
smart enough to bring some back-up.

729
00:37:33.651 --> 00:37:34.829
I wouldn't have to
come up here. Shawn.

730
00:37:34.853 --> 00:37:37.687
Shawn. will you tell them why
Walker wouldn't let them dig?

731
00:37:37.756 --> 00:37:39.657
Roger Deacon.

732
00:37:39.724 --> 00:37:41.659
Deacon is buried
on the property!

733
00:37:41.726 --> 00:37:45.527
Dad! Dad. you just
blew the big reveal.

734
00:37:45.597 --> 00:37:46.974
You already mentioned
his name. Shawn.

735
00:37:46.998 --> 00:37:51.094
They don't know that Deacon was
the partner Walker killed 20 years ago.

736
00:37:51.169 --> 00:37:52.569
Hey. now. wait a minute here.

737
00:37:52.637 --> 00:37:53.730
He what. now?

738
00:37:53.805 --> 00:37:57.242
Yeah. he killed Deacon and he
buried him somewhere on the farm.

739
00:37:57.308 --> 00:38:00.745
and he can't remember where.
Isn't that right. Farmer Shootypants?

740
00:38:00.812 --> 00:38:03.145
I don't have to stand
here and take this.

741
00:38:03.214 --> 00:38:05.240
No. actually. you do.

742
00:38:05.316 --> 00:38:06.927
What does this have to do
with Christopher Franzen?

743
00:38:06.951 --> 00:38:10.479
He killed Franzen when he caught him
standing above his dinosaur skull discovery.

744
00:38:10.555 --> 00:38:13.889
<i>sending him flying right
into the teeth of the dinosaur.</i>

745
00:38:13.958 --> 00:38:16.052
But he couldn't bury
him here. No. no. no.

746
00:38:16.127 --> 00:38:20.155
He had called the farm. he had snooped around
the farm. there was a trail to the farm. No.

747
00:38:20.231 --> 00:38:22.576
He had to dump him somewhere
where there would be no forensics.

748
00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:24.660
Like the ocean.

749
00:38:26.070 --> 00:38:31.236
Just let the saltwater clean the corpse
and wash it ashore. And the murder scene?

750
00:38:31.309 --> 00:38:34.871
<i>Well. he hopped on his handy
bulldozer and filled the hole.</i>

751
00:38:36.581 --> 00:38:39.278
I'm getting a bad
feeling about your streak.

752
00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:40.511
You. too. huh?

753
00:38:41.085 --> 00:38:42.849
I think I need a lawyer.

754
00:38:42.921 --> 00:38:44.765
I think you're right. Put
your hands behind your back.

755
00:38:44.789 --> 00:38:45.813
What? You heard me.

756
00:38:45.890 --> 00:38:49.170
You still haven't answered the question why
he dug all the holes around the house. Shawn.

757
00:38:49.194 --> 00:38:51.857
(WHISPERING)
Dad. that's the finale.

758
00:38:52.263 --> 00:38:54.630
That's why I don't
invite you to these things.

759
00:38:56.067 --> 00:38:59.970
He was looking for
Deacon's body. whatever.

760
00:39:00.038 --> 00:39:01.301
Are we done here. Mr. Spencer?

761
00:39:01.372 --> 00:39:03.102
No. we're not done.

762
00:39:03.174 --> 00:39:05.200
For my final demonstration.

763
00:39:07.078 --> 00:39:10.014
I will now discover a dinosaur.

764
00:39:10.081 --> 00:39:11.879
Shawn!

765
00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:14.044
Actually.

766
00:39:14.118 --> 00:39:15.814
Gus will discover a dinosaur.

767
00:39:16.888 --> 00:39:19.414
Wait a second. You just
want me to dig this hole.

768
00:39:19.490 --> 00:39:20.719
I do not.

769
00:39:20.792 --> 00:39:23.523
I'm not falling for that.
Shawny boy. You dig it.

770
00:39:23.595 --> 00:39:25.393
Fine. I'll take credit
for the discovery.

771
00:39:25.463 --> 00:39:27.091
Oh. no. you won't.
Give me that shovel.

772
00:39:27.165 --> 00:39:29.691
Whoa. whoa. whoa.
It's too late. You blew it.

773
00:39:29.767 --> 00:39:32.828
And whoever discovers it gets
to name it. I'm naming him Zippy.

774
00:39:32.904 --> 00:39:36.068
Or Chompy. Zippy the
Dinosaur. discovered by...

775
00:39:36.140 --> 00:39:38.234
By psychic paleo-sleuth.
Shawn Spencer.

776
00:39:38.309 --> 00:39:40.107
Give me this shovel. Shawn!

777
00:39:52.957 --> 00:39:54.357
Killed by a dinosaur.

778
00:39:55.093 --> 00:39:57.892
And he's right. It was
an actual dinosaur.

779
00:39:57.962 --> 00:40:00.864
Technically. it's the
fall that killed him.

780
00:40:00.932 --> 00:40:02.457
Not helping.

781
00:40:02.533 --> 00:40:04.559
Oh. come on. Who am
I kidding? I am doomed.

782
00:40:04.636 --> 00:40:07.765
I am never gonna suspect an extinct
creature. How can I compete with that?

783
00:40:07.839 --> 00:40:08.898
You don't have to compete.

784
00:40:08.973 --> 00:40:13.069
O'Hara. I am physically incapable
of pointing the finger at a dragon.

785
00:40:13.144 --> 00:40:15.841
or a leprechaun. or
the Loch Ness monster.

786
00:40:15.914 --> 00:40:17.780
I quit. I'm gonna donate
my badge to charity.

787
00:40:17.849 --> 00:40:21.149
It was a good run. Carlton.
All streaks have to end.

788
00:40:21.219 --> 00:40:24.417
Lou Boudreau fielded the ball
cleanly. You have to let it go.

789
00:40:25.323 --> 00:40:26.882
Who the hell is Lou Boudreau?

790
00:40:26.958 --> 00:40:30.588
He recorded the out that ended DiMaggio's
hit streak. Don't you watch baseball?

791
00:40:30.662 --> 00:40:33.607
Of course I watch baseball. I just don't
know meaningless facts from 75 years ago.

792
00:40:33.631 --> 00:40:34.724
Sixty-six.

793
00:40:34.799 --> 00:40:36.028
You disturb me.

794
00:40:39.003 --> 00:40:40.096
Do you need a hug?

795
00:40:40.171 --> 00:40:41.696
Oh. what do I look like?

796
00:40:48.112 --> 00:40:50.013
Yeah. I'll take the hug.

797
00:40:52.650 --> 00:40:53.913
Okay. thanks. Okay.

798
00:41:00.358 --> 00:41:04.489
Oh. come on. you guys. We're
still doing this intervention thing?

799
00:41:04.562 --> 00:41:06.292
Yes. Yes. Shawn. we are.

800
00:41:07.231 --> 00:41:10.531
Son. you have no
sense of responsibility.

801
00:41:10.601 --> 00:41:12.513
And lately. you've been
purposefully putting yourself

802
00:41:12.537 --> 00:41:14.301
in a severe amount
of unnecessary danger.

803
00:41:14.372 --> 00:41:17.069
On top of which. you are
constantly belittling the good...

804
00:41:17.141 --> 00:41:20.202
Actually. Henry. I
stretched the truth a bit.

805
00:41:20.278 --> 00:41:22.679
This isn't about Shawn.

806
00:41:22.747 --> 00:41:23.908
This is about you.

807
00:41:23.982 --> 00:41:24.982
What?

808
00:41:25.049 --> 00:41:28.451
Can we talk about your
obsessive need for control?

809
00:41:28.519 --> 00:41:31.978
You come into my house.
Devette. you lie to me?

810
00:41:32.056 --> 00:41:33.524
Let's try to be rational.

811
00:41:33.591 --> 00:41:38.586
Did you really drive all the way up to Ojai
just to crash Shawn's crowning moment?

812
00:41:39.664 --> 00:41:40.688
Get out.

813
00:41:40.765 --> 00:41:42.859
Henry. we're here for
you. At least listen...

814
00:41:42.934 --> 00:41:44.300
Out. now.

815
00:41:45.770 --> 00:41:49.172
Get out! Out!

816
00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:52.039
SHAWN: I'd like to start.
When I was about seven...

817
00:42:06.391 --> 00:42:10.055
<i>In between the lines
there's a lot of obscurity</i>

818
00:42:10.128 --> 00:42:13.565
<i>I'm not inclined to
resign to maturity</i>

819
00:42:13.631 --> 00:42:16.863
<i>If it's all right then
you're all wrong</i>

820
00:42:16.934 --> 00:42:21.463
<i>But why bounce around
to the same damn song?</i>

821
00:42:21.539 --> 00:42:27.809
<i>You'd rather run
when you can't crawl</i>

822
00:42:27.879 --> 00:42:31.316
<i>I know. you know That
I'm not telling the truth</i>

823
00:42:31.382 --> 00:42:34.375
<i>I know. you know They
just don't have any proof</i>

824
00:42:34.452 --> 00:42:37.718
<i>Embrace the deception
Learn how to bend</i>

825
00:42:37.789 --> 00:42:41.851
<i>Your worst inhibitions tend
to psych you out in the end</i>

826
00:42:41.926 --> 00:42:45.328
<i>I know. you know</i>

827
00:42:45.396 --> 00:42:48.230
<i>I know. you know</i>
